{{Infobox person | name = Alicia Haber | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1946|10|21|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Montevideo]], Uruguay | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Historian, art critic, curator, teacher | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | spouse = | children = | awards = | alma_mater = {{ill|Artigas Teachers Institute|es|Instituto de Profesores Artigas}} }} '''Alicia Haber''' (born 21 October 1946) is a [[Uruguay]]an historian, art critic, curator, and teacher.
==Biography== A graduate of the {{ill|Artigas Teachers Institute|es|Instituto de Profesores Artigas}}, Alicia Haber took three [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholarships]] in the United States, specializing in history and art criticism.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://arte.elpais.com.uy/author/aliciahaber/ |title=Notas del columnista: Alicia Haber |trans-title=Notes on the Columnist: Alicia Haber |work=[[El País (Uruguay)|El País]] Arte MUVA |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201005013/http://arte.elpais.com.uy/author/aliciahaber/ |archive-date=1 February 2016 |dead-url=yes |access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref> She was the chief curator of the Department of Culture of the {{ill|Municipality of Montevideo|es|Intendencia Departamental de Montevideo}} from 1988 to 2009. She was an art critic at the newspaper ''[[El País (Uruguay)|El País]]'' between 1982 and 2009.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Artes Visuales en Uruguay: diccionario crítico |trans-title=Visual Arts in Uruguay: Critical Dictionary |last=Di Maggio |first=Nelson |publisher=Gussi Libros |isbn=9789974991569 |language=Spanish |year=2013}}</ref> She has been director of the Virtual Museum of Arts (MUVA) of ''El País'' since its formation in 1996.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1091471-los-museos-llevan-su-arte-por-el-mundo-de-la-mano-de-internet |title=Los museos llevan su arte por el mundo de la mano de Internet |trans-title=Museums Take Their Art to the World Through the Internet |last=Rothschild |first=Saskia |work=[[La Nación]] |language=Spanish |date=20 January 2009 |access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref>
She has curated numerous exhibition projects for museums and cultural centers in her country and abroad. She was curator of the Uruguayan submission to the Biennial of Cuenca in 2001, and in 2005 was curator of [[Lacy Duarte]]'s exhibition at the [[Venice Biennale]]. She is the author of numerous monographs and critical texts for publications, catalogs, and art books.
