'''James S. Shapiro''' (born September 11, 1955) is Professor of [[English studies|English]] and [[Comparative Literature]] at [[Columbia University]] who specialises in Shakespeare and the Early Modern period. Shapiro has served on the faculty at Columbia University since 1985, teaching [[Shakespeare]] and other topics, and he has published widely on Shakespeare and [[Elizabethan era|Elizabethan culture]].

== Life ==
Shapiro was born and raised in [[Brooklyn]], New York, where he attended [[Midwood High School]]. He obtained his [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] at Columbia University in 1977, [[Master's degree]] in 1978 and [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] at [[University of Chicago]] in 1982. After teaching at [[Dartmouth College]] and [[Goucher College]], Shapiro joined the faculty at Columbia University in 1985. He taught as a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] lecturer at [[Bar-Ilan University]] and [[Tel Aviv University]] (1988–1989) and served as the Samuel Wanamaker Fellow at the [[Globe Theatre]] in London (1998).

Shapiro has received awards from the National Endowment for the Humanities, The Huntington Library, and the Memorial Foundation for Jewish Culture for his publications and academic activities. He has written for numerous periodicals, including ''The Chronicle of Higher Education'', ''The New York Times Book Review'', ''The Financial Times'', and ''The Daily Telegraph''.  In 2006, he was named a [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]] Fellow as well as a Fellow at the Cullman Center for Scholars and Writers at the New York Public Library.

Shapiro won the 2006 [[Samuel Johnson Prize]] as well as the 2006 Theatre Book Prize for his work ''1599: a Year in the Life of William Shakespeare''.<ref>''[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/14/AR2006061402454.html 'Shakespeare' Wins Samuel Johnson Prize]'', [[Washington Post]]/[[Associated Press|AP]], June 14, 2006</ref> He also won the 2011 George Freedley Memorial Award, given by the Theatre Library Association, for his study of the [[Shakespeare authorship question]], ''Contested Will: Who Wrote Shakespeare?'', which has been described as the "definitive treatment" of the [[Oxfordian theory]].<ref>''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' columnist [[Stephen Marche]] at [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/23/magazine/wouldnt-it-be-cool-if-shakespeare-wasnt-shakespeare.html?_r=1 'Wouldn’t It Be Cool if Shakespeare Wasn’t Shakespeare?,'] in [[The New York Times Magazine]], 21 October 2011.p.2: "If you want to read the definitive treatment, there is James Shapiro’s more recent ''Contested Will'', although that book is nearly as absurd as its subject, because using a brain like Shapiro’s on the authorship question is like bringing an F-22 to an alley knife fight."</ref> The same year Shapiro was inducted into the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]. His most recent book, "The Year of Lear: Shakespeare in 1606," was awarded the James Tait Black Prize for Biography <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Tait_Black_Memorial_Prize</ref>as well as the Sheridan Morley Prize for Theatre Biography.<ref>https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/James-Shapiro-Wins-9th-Annual-Sheridan-Morley-Prize-for-Theatre-Biography-20160302</ref>  He is currently at work on a book about Shakespeare in a divided America.   <ref>https://english.columbia.edu/people/profile/405</ref>

He is married, has a son, and lives in New York City.<ref>[[Chautauqua Institution]]: ''[http://www.chautauqua-inst.org/Lectures/shapiro.html James Shapiro]'', July 15, 2002</ref>

