'''Marcel Martel''' is a French Canadian historian. He currently holds the Avie Bennett Historica Chair in Canadian History at [[York University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aviebennettchair.info.yorku.ca/about/the-chair-holder/|title=The Chair Holder|last=|first=|date=|website=The Avie Bennett Historica Chair in Canadian History|publisher=[[York University]]|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-27}}</ref>
A student of [[Ramsay Cook]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=|title=Nation, Ideas, Identities: Essays in Honour of Ramsay Cook|editor-last=Behiels|editor-first=Michael Derek|editor-last2=Martel|editor-first2=Marcel|editor-last3=Cook|editor-first3=Ramsay|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=9780195414615|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> Martel has published extensively on topics ranging from [[Quebec nationalism|French Canadian nationalism]] to [[Drug policy of Canada|federal drug policy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://people.laps.yorku.ca/people.nsf/researcherprofile?readform&shortname=mmartel|title=Marcel Martel Faculty Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=Faculty of Liberal Arts & Professional Studies|publisher=[[York University]]|language=en|access-date=2018-02-27}}</ref> His book ''Le deuil d'un pays imaginé'' won the 1997 ''Prix Michel-Brunet'' from the {{Interlanguage link|Institut d'histoire de l'Amérique française|fr||WD=}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ferland|first=Catherine|date=2007|title=Martel, Marcel, Not This Time&nbsp;: Canadians, Public Policy, and the Marijuana Question, 1961-1975 (Toronto, University of Toronto Press, 2006), 277&nbsp;p.|url=https://www.erudit.org/fr/revues/haf/2007-v60-n4-haf1778/016543ar/|journal=Revue d'histoire de l'Amérique française|language=fr|volume=60|issue=4|doi=10.7202/016543ar|issn=0035-2357}}</ref> In 2017, Martel was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]].<ref>[https://excal.on.ca/five-york-professors-elected-to-royal-society-of-canada/ Five York professors elected to Royal Society of Canada], ''Excalibur'', October 2, 2017</ref>
