'''Villem Raam''' (30 May 1910 – 21 May 1996) was an [[Estonian people|Estonian]] [[art history|art historian]], [[art critic]] and [[conservator-restorer]]. His work in documenting and preserving the cultural heritage of [[Estonia]], not least during the [[Estonian SSR|Soviet occupation of Estonia]], contributed significantly to the understanding of art history and cultural heritage in Estonia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Randla|first1= Anneli|last2= |first2= |year= 2010|title= Villem Raam 100|journal= Baltic Journal of Art History|volume= |issue= 2010. Spring.|pages= |publisher= Chair of Art History of the Institute of History and Archaeology of the University of Tartu |doi= |url= http://ojs.utlib.ee/index.php/bjah/article/view/797|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref>
Villem Raam was born in [[Pärnu]] and studied art history at [[Tartu University]]. In 1938 he produced his first scholarly work on medieval Estonian architecture. Following the occupation of Estonia, in July 1940 Raam became the director of the State Art Museum of Soviet Estonia; however, in June 1941 he was arrested by Soviet authorities and deported to Siberia. He would remain in [[Gulag|labour camp]] for fifteen years. He was allowed to return to Estonia in 1956 and was able to continue working in his academic field, first as an employee at an institution with the purpose of registering architectural monuments. In 1957 he was admitted and eventually made a member of the board of the Estonian SSR Artists' Union. Subsequently he dedicated the rest of his life to art history, conservation issues and art criticism. Among his tangible contributions are the restoration of [[St. Nicholas' Church, Tallinn|St. Nicholas' church]] in [[Tallinn]], which he managed to convince the authorities to transform into a museum of ecclesiastical art rather than an initially planned "museum of atheism".<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Randla|first1= Anneli|last2= |first2= |year= 2010|title= Villem Raam 100|journal= Baltic Journal of Art History|volume= |issue= 2010. Spring.|pages= |publisher= Chair of Art History of the Institute of History and Archaeology of the University of Tartu |doi= |url= http://ojs.utlib.ee/index.php/bjah/article/view/797|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Hain|first1= Jüri|last2= |first2= |year= 2008|title= Villem Raam as an Art Critic|journal= Studies on Art and Architecture|volume= |issue= 3 (17)|pages= 83–99|publisher= Estonian Society of Art Historians |doi= |url= http://ktu.artun.ee/arh/eng_2008_17_3.html|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Hain|first1= Jüri|last2= |first2= |year= 2010|title= Villem Raam - the Keeper of Continuity of Art Culture|journal= Studies on Art and Architecture|volume= |issue= 19|pages= 160–162|publisher= Estonian Society of Art Historians |doi= |url= http://ktu.artun.ee/arh/pdf/ktu_2010_19_1_2_160_162_hain_sum.pdf|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref>
In 1996, Raam was awarded the [[Order of the National Coat of Arms]], 3rd class.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.president.ee/en/estonia/decorations/bearers.php?tm=Riigivapi+III+klassi+teenetem%C3%A4rk&pn=raam&en=|title= Estonian State Decorations|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= President of the Republic of Estonia|publisher= |accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref> Between June 2010 and May 2011, an exhibition his architectural photographs was made at the [[Art Museum of Estonia]] to mark the centenary of his birth.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nigulistemuuseum.ee/et/naitused/toimunud/8-est/sisulehed/369-raami-pildid-villem-raam-fotograafina|title= Raami pildid. Villem Raam fotograafina (In Estonian) |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |work= |publisher= Art Museum of Estonia|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>
